Deodorant is quite possibly the most carcinogenic product that we use on our bodies and we use it daily. To find an effective alternative is very difficult and could be very embarrassing if it doesn't work. I have tried many name brand alternatives and have found them to be ineffective and make you feel very slimy or sweaty. Yuck. Oddly enough, it was this somewhat simple recipe with effective essential oils that I found to work great and decided to package it myself so others could use it. Just rub a small amount under arms after shower and you're ready to go for the whole day! This deodorant really works, check out our feedback! It's all I use and it lasts all day. Money back guarantee. Talc free. Aluminum free. Paraben Free. Propylene Glycol Free. Triclosan Free. I combine baking soda, that alone works great for a time, with coconut oil which is naturally anti-bacterial, anti-fungal and does not leave a greasy feel. I add antibacterial essential oils for effectiveness and their awesome scent and viola! An all natural and effective deodorant. I LOVE this product, it works great and smells awesome! 

What others are saying: "I put this on before bed and there is absolutely no need to reapply in the morning. This deodorant held up through 104 degree weather in northern California. I am so happy I have found this and will continue to use this forever!" "This stuff works fabulous, I sit here 24 hours after I applied the deodorant and still fresh as a daisy , which is really amazing. More amazing is that my wife was raving about it before I even got to try it, and she resists anything organic"

â™¦ï¸Stripped downâ™¦ï¸Volume 1

So much has changed during this year. Its completely crazy to think that during only fee months of being stuck at home perspective changed so fucking much. 

â™¦ï¸Change number one: 
I don't care about clothes as much as I thought I did.
Clothes and value that society claims it brings is truly minimal. I've been wearing same shit on rotation for months. A month ago I got rid of a lot of things posting them for sale and putting them away or donating them. I felt scared to dive deep and be left with only a few things so I allowed myself a decent amount of options. I didn't wear more than half of them. The saddest revelation is all the Disney stuff I have, some of which I do wear in day to day but a lot of it is for park attire. This coming month I'm attempting 333 project. Still need to finish narrowing things down but I am pretty close. From now on I intend to make smarter purchasing choices and buy things that I need and is high quality not what's on sale and looks ok.

â™¦ï¸ Change number two:
Without Disneyland being a thing we do on the weekends priorities changed. 
I've been a regular at the parks for about 2 years or so. Before that I only would go once-twice a year at the most. With Disney becoming a lifestyle, and trust me, it truly is and will remain shopping for clothes and items changed. 
I loved shopping for outfits to wear at the park, new bag, cool Disney trinket for home. With the last one being somewhat useful previous two category became kinda obsolete. Like, I truly don't mind going into the parks in the civilian clothes now. It's fun to style looks in the parks but outside of the universe of the parks there is no real human need for a snow white dress and magic carpet purse. 
Will I sell them? Probably not. But I do thing that once parks open I'll have a separate box to dip into for Disney looks. It's the same box as Halloween things. ğŸ˜‚ and to finish this one: am I still going to buy things at the parks? Yes. I collect pins and have a board for them and I get one each visit. I intend to focus on need vs want when shopping at the park.

More changes in posts to follow...
